{"title_page": "Competition and Markets Authority", "text_new": "{{short description|UK government non-ministerial department}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date= April 2013}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Competition and Markets Authority\n| type = Authority\n| seal = \n| seal_caption = \n| logo = Competition and Markets Authority.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| formed = 1 October 2013\n| preceding1 = \n| dissolved = \n| jurisdiction = [[United Kingdom]]\n| headquarters = [[London]]\n| coordinates = \n| employees = \n| budget = \n| minister1_name = \n| minister1_pfo = \n| chief1_name = [[Andrew Tyrie]]\n| chief1_position = Chairman\n| chief2_name = [[Andrea Coscelli]]\n| chief2_position = Chief Executive\n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]\n| child1_agency = \n| keydocument1 = \n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| map = \n| map_caption = \n| footnotes = \n| agency_type = [[Non-ministerial government department]]\n| agency_name = Competition and Markets Authority<br><small>{{lang-cy|Cystadleuaeth a Marchnadoedd Awdurdod}}</small>\n| nativename = \n| nativename_a = \n| nativename_r = \n| logo_width = \n| seal_width = \n| picture = \n| picture_width = \n| picture_caption = \n| superseding = \n| map_width = \n}}\nThe '''Competition and Markets Authority''' ('''CMA''')  is a [[non-ministerial government department]] in the [[United Kingdom]], responsible for strengthening business competition and preventing and reducing anti-competitive activities. The CMA launched in shadow form on 1 October 2013 and began operating fully on 1 April 2014, when it assumed many of the functions of the previously existing [[Competition Commission]] and [[Office of Fair Trading]], which were abolished.\n\n==Formation==\nOn 15 March 2012 the [[UK Government]]'s [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] (BIS) announced proposals for strengthening competition in the UK by merging the [[Office of Fair Trading]] and the [[Competition Commission (United Kingdom)|Competition Commission]] to create a new single Competition and Markets Authority (CMA).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/strengthening-competition-and-creating-a-single-competition-and-markets-authority-cma--2 \n|title=Strengthening competition and creating a single competition and markets authority (CMA) \n|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=15 March 2012 |publisher=Department for Business Innovation & Skills |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The formation of the CMA was enacted in Part 3 of the [[Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/24/part/3/enacted |title=Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013, Part 3 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=25 April 2013 |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref> which received [[royal assent]] on 25 April 2013.\n\nIn July 2012, [[David Currie, Baron Currie of Marylebone|Lord Currie]] was appointed Chairman designate of the CMA and in January 2013 [[Alex Chisholm]] was appointed Chief Executive designate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130108/wmstext/130108m0001.htm#13010823000041 |title=Competition and Markets Authority |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=8 January 2013 |work=Ministerial statement by Vince Cable |publisher=Hansard |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The term 'designate' was dropped when the CMA was launched on 1 October 2013.\n\nOn 15 July 2013 BIS announced the first stage of an open public consultation period and published a summary, setting out the background to the consultation and inviting views on the draft guidance for the CMA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/competition-and-markets-authority-guidance-part-1 |title=Competition and Markets Authority - Open consultation guidance |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=15 July 2013 |publisher=Department for Business, Innovation & Skills |accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>  The first stage of the consultation ended on 6 September 2013. On 17 September, BIS announced the second stage of the consultation, which closed on 7 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/competition-and-markets-authority-guidance-part-2 |title=Competition and Markets Authority guidance, Part 2 |date=17 September 2013 |publisher=Department for Business Innovation and Skills, UK Government |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2013 and 2014, the CMA announced several waves of appointments at director level, reporting to members of the senior executive team.<ref>Appointments at Director level:<br>seven: {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-further-appointments |title=CMA announces further appointments |date=6 November 2013 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=8 November 2013}}<br>eighteen {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-next-wave-of-senior-appointments|title=Second wave of appointments |date=14 November 2013 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=24 December 2013}}<br>eighteen {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-third-wave-of-director-appointments|title=Third wave of appointments |date=13 December 2013 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=24 December 2013}}<br>eleven {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-further-wave-of-director-appointments |title=Further wave of appointments |date=24 January 2014 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2014 the CMA published the Rules of Procedure for CMA merger, market and special reference groups<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/298801/CMA17.pdf |title= Rules of Procedure for Merger, Market and Special Reference Groups |date=28 March 2014 |publisher=CMA |accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref>\nfollowing a consultation which ran from 21 February to 18 March.\n\nOn 26 July 2017, Andrea Coscelli was appointed Chief Executive Officer of the Competition and Markets Authority.<ref name=\"Andrea\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/andrea-coscelli-named-ceo-of-competition-and-markets-authority|title=Andrea Coscelli named CEO of Competition and Markets Authority|publisher=UK Government|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 June 2018, Andrew Tyrie took up his role as the new Chair of the CMA, taking over from [[David Currie, Baron Currie of Marylebone|Lord Currie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/andrew-tyrie-begins-as-chair-of-competition-and-markets-authority|title=Andrew Tyrie begins as Chair of Competition and Markets Authority|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 August 2019, The CMA\u2018s London office moved to The Cabot, 25 Cabot Square, Canary Wharf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-completes-move-to-canary-wharf|title=CMA completes move to Canary Wharf|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Responsibilities==\n{{see also|English contract law|EU competition law}}\nIn situations where competition could be unfair or consumer choice may be affected, the CMA is responsible for:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/competition-and-markets-authority/about \n|title=CMA Responsibilities \n|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n* investigating phase 1 and phase 2 mergers<ref>https://www.gov.uk/topic/competition/mergers</ref>\n* conducting market studies and market investigations<ref>https://www.gov.uk/topic/competition/markets</ref>\n* investigating possible breaches of prohibitions against anti-competitive agreements under the [[Competition Act 1998]]\n* bringing criminal proceedings against individuals who commit cartels offences\n* enforcing consumer protection legislation, particularly the [[Unfair Terms in Consumer Contract Directive]] and [[Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1999|Regulations]]\n* encouraging regulators to use their competition powers\n* considering regulatory references and appeals\n\n== Strategic Goals ==\nThe CMA currently lists 5 strategic goals:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/competition-and-markets-authority/about|title=About us|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n* delivering effective enforcement \u2013 to deter wrongdoing, protect consumers and educate businesses\n* extending competition frontiers \u2013 by using the markets regime to improve the way competition works, in particular within the regulated sectors\n* refocusing consumer protection \u2013 working with its partners to promote compliance and understanding of the law, and empowering consumers to make informed choices\n* achieving professional excellence \u2013 by managing every case efficiently, transparently and fairly, and ensuring all legal, economic and financial analysis is conducted to the highest international standards\n* developing integrated performance \u2013 through ensuring that all staff are brought together from different professional backgrounds to form effective multi-disciplinary teams and provide a trusted competition adviser across government\n\n==CMA Board and Senior Executive team==\n*[[Andrew Tyrie|The Rt Hon Lord Andrew Tyrie]], Chair<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrew-tyrie|title=The Rt Hon Lord Andrew Tyrie - GOV.UK|website=gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n* [[Andrea Coscelli|Dr Andrea Coscelli]], Chief Executive <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/competition-and-markets-authority/about/our-governance|title=Our governance|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n* Dr Michael Grenfell, Executive Director, Enforcement<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-appoints-new-executive-director\n|title=CMA appoints new Executive Director\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Andrea Gomes da Silva, Executive Director, Markets and Mergers<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Erik Wilson, Executive Director, Corporate Services<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/people/erik-wilson\n|title=Erik Wilson \u2013 biography and role\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref>\n* [[William Kovacic]],  Non-Executive Director<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/william-kovacic\n|title= William Kovacic \u2013 biography\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Alan Giles]], Non-Executive Director<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/alan-giles\n|title= Alan Giles \u2013 biography\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 October 2013 }}</ref>\n* Dr [[Amelia Fletcher]] OBE, Non-Executive Director<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/amelia-fletcher\n|title= Amelia Fletcher OBE \u2013 biography\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 December 2017 }}</ref>\n*Jonathon Scott, Non-Executive Director<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Martin Coleman, Non-Executive Director<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Cynthia Dubin, Non-Executive Director<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-non-executive-director-and-panel-members-appointed-to-the-competition-and-markets-authority-board|title=New non-executive director and panel members appointed to the Competition and Markets Authority board|last=Clark|first=Greg|date=7 February 2019|work=GOV.UK|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Kirstin Baker, Panel Member Non-Executive Director<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Dr Mike Walker, Chief Economic Adviser (attends meetings and provides advice to the Board)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Sarah Cardell, General Counsel (attends meetings and provides advice to the Board)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn December 2019 the Commission released a report with recommendations to curtail the duopoly of Google and Facebook. The general election meant that the report was not presented to the Government in December. So ideas like sharing their 90% share of our online data with other companies has not been acted upon.<ref> https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/dec/18/google-facebook-dominance-curbed-cma-report-uk-digital-market?CMP=Share_iOSApp_Other</ref>\n\nThe UK Competition Commission ruled several times against [[MyFerryLink]], so it could no longer operate from Dover despite the French competition authority authorising cross-channel activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meretmarine.com/fr/content/lautorite-de-la-concurrence-autorise-eurotunnel-racheter-la-flotte-de-seafrance|title=L'autorit\u00e9 de la concurrence autorise Eurotunnel \u00e0 racheter la flotte de SeaFrance|date=14 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref> The French government blamed the decision to ban one out of three ferry operators on fair-trade concerns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/Frederic-Cuvillier-condamne-la.html|title=French Ministry of Transport blame CMA decision|publisher=}}</ref> The appeals court overturned these rulings<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/Articles/2015/05/26/54301/appeal-bid-against-myferrylink-ruling-turned-down.html|title=}}</ref> because MyFerryLink was not a merger of the bankrupt SeaFrance and [[Eurotunnel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/sea_france_final_-15_05-_15_2.pdf|title=Judge decision in Scop SeaFrance against CMA|publisher=}}</ref> MyFerryLink called attention to a potential conflict of interest, pointing out that the former accountant of [[DFDS]] (the competitor and plaintiff) was now a member of the UK Competition Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/societes/2014/06/28/20005-20140628ARTFIG00004-myferrylink-interdit-de-sejour-en-angleterre.php|title=MyFerryLink interdit de s\u00e9jour en Angleterre|date=28 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> Following these delays, Eurotunnel (owner of the boats rented to MyFerryLink) sold two new boats to the DFDS competitor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/economie/myferrylink-eurotunnel-cede-deux-bateaux-au-danois-dfds-08-06-2015-4843661.php|title=MyFerryLink : Eurotunnel c\u00e8de deux bateaux au Danois DFDS|date=8 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Because of this the port of [[Calais]] was blocked by workers, boats were occupied and the [[Channel Tunnel]] attacked, resulting in cross-channel disruption and traffic jams in the UK and France.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-33340850|title=Travel chaos as strike continues|date=1 July 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe UK Competition Commission ruled against the merger between [[Illumina, Inc.|Illumina]] and [[Pacific Biosciences]] in 2019. Some experts in the field of DNA sequencing considered that this would be bad news for Pacific Biosciences,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SanDiegOmics/status/1207055195256963072|title=Really seems like the merger won\u2019t happen. I think that\u2019s bad news for @PacBio fans, but I hope I\u2019m wrong.https://twitter.com/OmicsOmicsBlog/status/1207048165779787777 \u2026|last=Baker|first=Shawn|date=2019-12-17|website=@SanDiegOmics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> although others considered the UK CMA's decision to be within their remit. The US [[Federal Trade Commission]] argued along the same lines as the UK CMA's decision later in 2019.\n\n==Healthcare==\nDuring an inquiry into the private healthcare market the authority made the Private Healthcare Market Investigation Order 2014.  This requires healthcare providers, including [[NHS trusts]] to submit information to the [[Private Healthcare Information Network]].  This will include information about infection rates, rates of adverse incidents, and the relative health improvement brought about by treatments.  This will be broken down by consultant in 2018 and in 2019 will extend to charges.<ref>{{cite news|title=Competition regulator urgently demands data from trusts|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/7018043.article?mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiT0dJME5qSXlabUl3T0RCbSIsInQiOiJZY3VRQk0rdXA4cTRmTFJcL0ltUTM3SkE2VkJzb3kwNTBtMUU2NlR3NmpYWEtOUFJNRkJcL0NXK1wvU2p6bGRtUVBiclBQM2JwVGtJR0lJRyszSG5XdjBHNWZvSW1veXZNUE9rMzB3SFdpTUFESFpsRlVKeURYNGpsVGtNNCtxM3Y2YiJ9|accessdate=18 May 2017|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[English contract law]]\n*[[EU competition law]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/24/contents/enacted |title=Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cma-structure|title=CMA structure|publisher=UK Government}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/cma-cases |title=CMA cases |publisher=UK Government}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/CMAgovUK/ CMA Facebook page]\n*[https://twitter.com/cmagovuk CMA on Twitter]\n{{Departments of the United Kingdom Government}}\n{{Economy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2013 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Competition regulators]]\n[[Category:Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:Non-ministerial departments of the United Kingdom Government]]\n[[Category:Financial regulatory authorities of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Consumer organisations in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|UK government non-ministerial department}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date= April 2013}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Competition and Markets Authority\n| type = Authority\n| seal = \n| seal_caption = \n| logo = Competition and Markets Authority.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| formed = 1 October 2013\n| preceding1 = \n| dissolved = \n| jurisdiction = [[United Kingdom]]\n| headquarters = [[London]]\n| coordinates = \n| employees = \n| budget = \n| minister1_name = \n| minister1_pfo = \n| chief1_name = [[Andrew Tyrie]]\n| chief1_position = Chairman\n| chief2_name = [[Andrea Coscelli]]\n| chief2_position = Chief Executive\n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]\n| child1_agency = \n| keydocument1 = \n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| map = \n| map_caption = \n| footnotes = \n| agency_type = [[Non-ministerial government department]]\n| agency_name = Competition and Markets Authority<br><small>{{lang-cy|Cystadleuaeth a Marchnadoedd Awdurdod}}</small>\n| nativename = \n| nativename_a = \n| nativename_r = \n| logo_width = \n| seal_width = \n| picture = \n| picture_width = \n| picture_caption = \n| superseding = \n| map_width = \n}}\nThe '''Competition and Markets Authority''' ('''CMA''')  is a [[non-ministerial government department]] in the [[United Kingdom]], responsible for strengthening business competition and preventing and reducing anti-competitive activities. The CMA launched in shadow form on 1 October 2013 and began operating fully on 1 April 2014, when it assumed many of the functions of the previously existing [[Competition Commission]] and [[Office of Fair Trading]], which were abolished.\n\n==Formation==\nOn 15 March 2012 the [[UK Government]]'s [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] (BIS) announced proposals for strengthening competition in the UK by merging the [[Office of Fair Trading]] and the [[Competition Commission (United Kingdom)|Competition Commission]] to create a new single Competition and Markets Authority (CMA).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/strengthening-competition-and-creating-a-single-competition-and-markets-authority-cma--2 \n|title=Strengthening competition and creating a single competition and markets authority (CMA) \n|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=15 March 2012 |publisher=Department for Business Innovation & Skills |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The formation of the CMA was enacted in Part 3 of the [[Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/24/part/3/enacted |title=Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013, Part 3 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=25 April 2013 |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref> which received [[royal assent]] on 25 April 2013.\n\nIn July 2012, [[David Currie, Baron Currie of Marylebone|Lord Currie]] was appointed Chairman designate of the CMA and in January 2013 [[Alex Chisholm]] was appointed Chief Executive designate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130108/wmstext/130108m0001.htm#13010823000041 |title=Competition and Markets Authority |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=8 January 2013 |work=Ministerial statement by Vince Cable |publisher=Hansard |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The term 'designate' was dropped when the CMA was launched on 1 October 2013.\n\nOn 15 July 2013 BIS announced the first stage of an open public consultation period and published a summary, setting out the background to the consultation and inviting views on the draft guidance for the CMA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/competition-and-markets-authority-guidance-part-1 |title=Competition and Markets Authority - Open consultation guidance |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=15 July 2013 |publisher=Department for Business, Innovation & Skills |accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>  The first stage of the consultation ended on 6 September 2013. On 17 September, BIS announced the second stage of the consultation, which closed on 7 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/competition-and-markets-authority-guidance-part-2 |title=Competition and Markets Authority guidance, Part 2  |date=17 September 2013 |publisher=Department for Business Innovation and Skills, UK Government |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2013 and 2014, the CMA announced several waves of appointments at director level, reporting to members of the senior executive team.<ref>Appointments at Director level:<br>seven: {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-further-appointments |title=CMA announces further appointments |date=6 November 2013 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=8 November 2013}}<br>eighteen {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-next-wave-of-senior-appointments|title=Second wave of appointments |date=14 November 2013 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=24 December 2013}}<br>eighteen {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-third-wave-of-director-appointments|title=Third wave of appointments |date=13 December 2013 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=24 December 2013}}<br>eleven {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/competition-and-markets-authority-announces-further-wave-of-director-appointments |title=Further wave of appointments |date=24 January 2014 |publisher=Competition and Markets Authority, UK Government |accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2014 the CMA published the Rules of Procedure for CMA merger, market and special reference groups<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/298801/CMA17.pdf |title= Rules of Procedure for Merger, Market and Special Reference Groups |date=28 March 2014 |publisher=CMA |accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref>\nfollowing a consultation which ran from 21 February to 18 March.\n\nOn 26 July 2017, Andrea Coscelli was appointed Chief Executive Officer of the Competition and Markets Authority.<ref name=\"Andrea\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/andrea-coscelli-named-ceo-of-competition-and-markets-authority|title=Andrea Coscelli named CEO of Competition and Markets Authority|publisher=UK Government|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 June 2018, Andrew Tyrie took up his role as the new Chair of the CMA, taking over from [[David Currie, Baron Currie of Marylebone|Lord Currie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/andrew-tyrie-begins-as-chair-of-competition-and-markets-authority|title=Andrew Tyrie begins as Chair of Competition and Markets Authority|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 August 2019, The CMA\u2018s London office moved to The Cabot, 25 Cabot Square, Canary Wharf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-completes-move-to-canary-wharf|title=CMA completes move to Canary Wharf|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Responsibilities==\n{{see also|English contract law|EU competition law}}\nIn situations where competition could be unfair or consumer choice may be affected, the CMA is responsible for:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/competition-and-markets-authority/about \n|title=CMA Responsibilities \n|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n* investigating phase 1 and phase 2 mergers<ref>https://www.gov.uk/topic/competition/mergers</ref>\n* conducting market studies and market investigations<ref>https://www.gov.uk/topic/competition/markets</ref>\n* investigating possible breaches of prohibitions against anti-competitive agreements under the [[Competition Act 1998]]\n* bringing criminal proceedings against individuals who commit cartels offences\n* enforcing consumer protection legislation, particularly the [[Unfair Terms in Consumer Contract Directive]] and [[Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1999|Regulations]]\n* encouraging regulators to use their competition powers\n* considering regulatory references and appeals\n\n== Strategic Goals ==\nThe CMA currently lists 5 strategic goals:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/competition-and-markets-authority/about|title=About us|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n* delivering effective enforcement \u2013 to deter wrongdoing, protect consumers and educate businesses\n* extending competition frontiers \u2013 by using the markets regime to improve the way competition works, in particular within the regulated sectors\n* refocusing consumer protection \u2013 working with its partners to promote compliance and understanding of the law, and empowering consumers to make informed choices\n* achieving professional excellence \u2013 by managing every case efficiently, transparently and fairly, and ensuring all legal, economic and financial analysis is conducted to the highest international standards\n* developing integrated performance \u2013 through ensuring that all staff are brought together from different professional backgrounds to form effective multi-disciplinary teams and provide a trusted competition adviser across government\n\n==CMA Board and Senior Executive team==\n*[[Andrew Tyrie|The Rt Hon Lord Andrew Tyrie]], Chair<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrew-tyrie|title=The Rt Hon Lord Andrew Tyrie - GOV.UK|website=gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n* [[Andrea Coscelli|Dr Andrea Coscelli]], Chief Executive <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/competition-and-markets-authority/about/our-governance|title=Our governance|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n* Dr Michael Grenfell, Executive Director, Enforcement<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-appoints-new-executive-director\n|title=CMA appoints new Executive Director\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Andrea Gomes da Silva, Executive Director, Markets and Mergers<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Erik Wilson, Executive Director, Corporate Services<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/people/erik-wilson\n|title=Erik Wilson \u2013 biography and role\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref>\n* [[William Kovacic]],  Non-Executive Director<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/william-kovacic\n|title= William Kovacic \u2013 biography\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Alan Giles]], Non-Executive Director<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/alan-giles\n|title= Alan Giles \u2013 biography\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 October 2013 }}</ref>\n* Dr [[Amelia Fletcher]] OBE, Non-Executive Director<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/amelia-fletcher\n|title= Amelia Fletcher OBE \u2013 biography\n|publisher= UK Government\n|accessdate=20 December 2017 }}</ref>\n*Jonathon Scott, Non-Executive Director<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Martin Coleman, Non-Executive Director<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Cynthia Dubin, Non-Executive Director<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-non-executive-director-and-panel-members-appointed-to-the-competition-and-markets-authority-board|title=New non-executive director and panel members appointed to the Competition and Markets Authority board|last=Clark|first=Greg|date=7 February 2019|work=GOV.UK|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Kirstin Baker, Panel Member Non-Executive Director<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Dr Mike Walker, Chief Economic Adviser (attends meetings and provides advice to the Board)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Sarah Cardell, General Counsel (attends meetings and provides advice to the Board)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn December 2019 the Commission released a report with recommendations to curtail the duopoly of Google and Facebook. The general election meant that the report was not presented to the Government in December. So ideas like sharing their 90% share of our online data with other companies has not been acted upon.<ref> https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/dec/18/google-facebook-dominance-curbed-cma-report-uk-digital-market?CMP=Share_iOSApp_Other</ref>\n\nThe UK Competition Commission ruled several times against [[MyFerryLink]], so it could no longer operate from Dover despite the French competition authority authorising cross-channel activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meretmarine.com/fr/content/lautorite-de-la-concurrence-autorise-eurotunnel-racheter-la-flotte-de-seafrance|title=L'autorit\u00e9 de la concurrence autorise Eurotunnel \u00e0 racheter la flotte de SeaFrance|date=14 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref> The French government blamed the decision to ban one out of three ferry operators on fair-trade concerns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.developpement-durable.gouv.fr/Frederic-Cuvillier-condamne-la.html|title=French Ministry of Transport blame CMA decision|publisher=}}</ref> The appeals court overturned these rulings<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/Articles/2015/05/26/54301/appeal-bid-against-myferrylink-ruling-turned-down.html|title=}}</ref> because MyFerryLink was not a merger of the bankrupt SeaFrance and [[Eurotunnel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/sea_france_final_-15_05-_15_2.pdf|title=Judge decision in Scop SeaFrance against CMA|publisher=}}</ref> MyFerryLink called attention to a potential conflict of interest, pointing out that the former accountant of [[DFDS]] (the competitor and plaintiff) was now a member of the UK Competition Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/societes/2014/06/28/20005-20140628ARTFIG00004-myferrylink-interdit-de-sejour-en-angleterre.php|title=MyFerryLink interdit de s\u00e9jour en Angleterre|date=28 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> Following these delays, Eurotunnel (owner of the boats rented to MyFerryLink) sold two new boats to the DFDS competitor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/economie/myferrylink-eurotunnel-cede-deux-bateaux-au-danois-dfds-08-06-2015-4843661.php|title=MyFerryLink : Eurotunnel c\u00e8de deux bateaux au Danois DFDS|date=8 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Because of this the port of [[Calais]] was blocked by workers, boats were occupied and the [[Channel Tunnel]] attacked, resulting in cross-channel disruption and traffic jams in the UK and France.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-33340850|title=Travel chaos as strike continues|date=1 July 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe UK Competition Commission ruled against the merger between [[Illumina, Inc.|Illumina]] and [[Pacific Biosciences]] in 2019. Some experts in the field of DNA sequencing considered that this would be bad news for Pacific Biosciences,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SanDiegOmics/status/1207055195256963072|title=Really seems like the merger won\u2019t happen. I think that\u2019s bad news for @PacBio  fans, but I hope I\u2019m wrong.https://twitter.com/OmicsOmicsBlog/status/1207048165779787777\u00a0\u2026|last=Baker|first=Shawn|date=2019-12-17|website=@SanDiegOmics|language=en|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> although others considered the UK CMA's decision to be within their remit. The US [[Federal Trade Commission]] argued along the same lines as the UK CMA's decision later in 2019.\n\n==Healthcare==\nDuring an inquiry into the private healthcare market the authority made the Private Healthcare Market Investigation Order 2014.  This requires healthcare providers, including [[NHS trusts]] to submit information to the [[Private Healthcare Information Network]].  This will include information about infection rates, rates of adverse incidents, and the relative health improvement brought about by treatments.  This will be broken down by consultant in 2018 and in 2019 will extend to charges.<ref>{{cite news|title=Competition regulator urgently demands data from trusts|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/7018043.article?mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiT0dJME5qSXlabUl3T0RCbSIsInQiOiJZY3VRQk0rdXA4cTRmTFJcL0ltUTM3SkE2VkJzb3kwNTBtMUU2NlR3NmpYWEtOUFJNRkJcL0NXK1wvU2p6bGRtUVBiclBQM2JwVGtJR0lJRyszSG5XdjBHNWZvSW1veXZNUE9rMzB3SFdpTUFESFpsRlVKeURYNGpsVGtNNCtxM3Y2YiJ9|accessdate=18 May 2017|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[English contract law]]\n*[[EU competition law]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/24/contents/enacted |title=Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cma-structure|title=CMA structure|publisher=UK Government}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/cma-cases |title=CMA cases |publisher=UK Government}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/CMAgovUK/ CMA Facebook page]\n*[https://twitter.com/cmagovuk CMA on Twitter]\n{{Depa